To terminate a C program, you can use the `exit()` function from the `stdlib.h` library. This function takes an integer as an argument, which represents the program's exit status. A status of 0 typically indicates successful execution, while non-zero values can indicate errors.

Here's a basic example of how to use `exit()`:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    // Your program code here...
    printf("Program execution completed.\n");
    exit(0); // Exit with status 0
    return 0;
}
```

Alternatively, you can use `return` statement at the end of the `main()` function to terminate the program. The `return` statement can take an integer value, similar to `exit()`, to indicate the program's exit status.

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    // Your program code here...
    printf("Program execution completed.\n");
    return 0; // Exit with status 0
}
```

Note that `exit()` and `return` from `main()` are not exactly the same. `exit()` can be used from any function, not just `main()`, and it can be used to terminate
